segments.text: It's quite a stressful condition to be in a situation where you're having your first child and you get there, of course, when there was also another woman, a young woman, that was in labor at the same time.
And I didn't really understand all the things that were going on, but of course I wanted to see my wife get some attention.
As it turns out, the doctor was running back and forth from one patient to another.
And I guess I was sitting there with this young husband of the Indian girl who was also having a baby.
And he came out and explained that they were having a very difficult time with her and

they really didn't know if they were going to be able to save either the baby or the mother and of course for me this was almost like striking terror into the into the heart and but I calmed down and you know I realized that we were dealing with a very difficult situation and so the fact that
Joy wasn't getting much attention, I realized that, you know, there was some very difficult things going on.
As it turns out, she actually had the baby in her street clothes because, you know, there really wasn't time to do much other than just
sort of react.
It was almost like, I guess, in the United States that you have a baby in a taxi cab or something like that.
They were certainly in the delivery room, but there was, I guess, very little electricity.
Electricity was always sort of going off and on, and water was always going off and on, and so you can never guarantee that you're going to have really any
of the critical things when you need them.
And so it was rather primitive conditions to have our first child, but as it turns out, everything worked out.
And did she have leave from the university, or did you all have to take turns taking care of the child?
I guess the classes were already over,
We were going to be replaced by new volunteers that were coming in to take over the next year's teaching classes.
So basically what we were doing was kind of interacting with the new volunteers who were coming in.
There would be a little bit of overlap until they started into their new program.
And so we were just kind of into a handoff stage then.
So I guess at that point.
That's also summer vacation.
Yeah, it was going into the summer vacation.
And we would be, I guess, preparing to teach the high school kids again for the entrance exam type of work.
Did you feel that you were helping the locals on a day-to-day basis?
Well, I think so.
There was always question whether they saw you that much differently from, you know, any university professor.
As it turns out, the pay for university professors there was rather poor, and most of them had to have two jobs anyway.
So, you know, you could say one or the other jobs was kind of secondary.
So, they saw at least one person that was given full-time to the job, and maybe the other person had to hold down several jobs.
But, I don't know, I think they were more curious about
foreigners and they were always wanting to come and talk to you about other kinds of situations, mostly political ones.
There's a lot of political activism in Latin American universities and so they like to get into a lot of political discussions and so they would certainly
take the opportunity to draw you into discussions on various kinds of political issues.
And once again, how many years did you participate, and what were they?
From the years 1964 to 1966.
So each one of the Peace Corps assignments was generally two years.
And we started in June.
The first part of the assignment was actually a three-month period of training in the University of Washington in Seattle.
So that's the reason why, even though we didn't get into the country until, say, August or September,
that our Peace Corps two-year assignment actually ended in June because of the sort of three-month training period when you first start out.
They try to gear it so that you get in country at the time just before the new classes are going to start.
And that will end at the time that the second year's classes ends.
How many other volunteers were stationed locally, or you know, that you could interact with?
When I originally got into country, I was with three other Peace Corps volunteers, and we were all, we all started off living with the same Bolivian family, and then
It wasn't too long after that that we all kind of split up and moved in with different families.
So I think there was probably
maybe seven or eight Peace Corps volunteers that were working in La Paz and then we would see other volunteers that were working up on the Altiplano occasionally when they came back in.
There was a Peace Corps office in La Paz and so we saw a lot of the people when they would travel back in
to the Peace Corps office.
They may have some business to take care of in the office.
Maybe they were trying to get some additional medical materials or they would just come back in for periodic debriefings and so forth.
Maybe they also had to come in for physical exams.
And so we did interact with some of the people out in the outlying areas.
Did they come back?
They were stationed in more isolated villages.
Did they come back with any interesting stories about what they encountered?
Well, some of them were up on the Altiplano living in very small Indian villages.
These people would either be in public health or in community development.
And we also had other Peace Corps volunteers that were in the jungles up in Rurinabaki and Ribera Alta and so forth, up in what they call the Alto Beni.
Of course, there were a lot of sort of jungle stories that came back from there about their experiences with things like pythons and wild boars and all this sort of stuff.
But they're just kind of quite challenging things that can happen.
Okay, see you later.
See you late tonight.
Yeah.
Bye.
Bye.
There was one situation where in the Altiplano, they drink this drink called corn beer, which is chicha.
The way they brew it, you actually chew the corn mash, and then they
let the saliva go into this bowl and then it starts to ferment and then it gradually turns into what they call this corn beer.
And so some of the volunteers were at a party and they felt that it was going to be, if they didn't

uh, drink this, uh, this chicha, you know, that, uh, they're probably gonna, uh, create some kind of an incident where they would, people would feel that, you know, they were, uh, you know, not taking advantage of all the good things that they were being offered.
And, uh, so they decided to go ahead and taste it.
It tasted pretty good.
Uh, and later on when they were on a, a bus trip, uh, of course they, they got, uh,

really some intestinal cramps and so they were looking for an opportunity when the bus stopped to relieve some of their pressure that they had and so they had to run off into the bushes and one of them had actually some accident with his bowels and
And so he was trying to hang his shorts up on this little fence that were there and then
before he realized what was going on.
This pig, there were some pigs in the area and they actually came over and grabbed his shorts and ate the shorts.
So, here he was kind of in a situation where he was going to have to make the rest of the trip without his undershorts.
But, you know, he just kind of learned to roll with the punches.
But there were all kinds of situations.
Another instance where the difference in cultures and the way you have to do things was one of the Peace Corps volunteers that was living with another Bolivian family in La Paz.
They were trying to explain to her how to heat the water in the bathtub.
You fill the bathtub up, and then you put in this electrical resistor, which is called a raya flotante.
And so she had this thing in there, and it was heating the water.
And they failed to tell her never to stick her hand in or, you know, never to get into the water without first turning the,
Raya Floatante off because you're actually electrifying the water and water is a tremendous conductor of electricity.

Anyway, she was all prepared for her bath and just kind of stuck her finger into the water to see if the water was warm enough and if she could take the Raya Floatante out and of course she got a tremendous electrical shock and she was
flew out of the bathroom and actually ran out into the house where the rest of the Bolivian family was.
And here she is, naked.
And of course, they had to calm her down.
And they were, I guess, all very happy that she wasn't electrocuted.
She was one of the volunteers.
Yes, she was one of the volunteers.
But you never realize all these kind
things that we take for granted.
A simple thing like a shower and sometimes how difficult it is to adjust to these sort of new conditions.
I guess I'm going to double check this.
Okay, my next question.
You were mentioning about showers and things like that.
What were your facilities like?
Were your living quarters
We actually had pretty nice quarters with the Bolivian families that we were living with.
And then after we got married, then we had a little apartment that we took.
And other than the fact that there was no hot water and that there was no central heating in order to say even

read or prepare for your lesson plans, or if you wanted to read Time magazine in the evening, you had to basically have sweaters and jackets on in the house, and then because the electricity was probably going to go out, you also had to have a lot of candles and lanterns ready for the time when there was sort of a planned

electrical brownout almost daily and also the water was generally turned off by say like eight o'clock in the evening and what they actually had to do is that they had real old plumbing systems and so the plumbing actually the sewage

sort of was just backing up and sitting there during the daytime and so then there was one main conduit that they had to use to drain off all of the sewage so at about eight o'clock they would turn off the water and then open this main valve and then you know run all the sewage down through that and so you couldn't
flush the toilet or anything like that any time after 8 o'clock in the evening.
So that was always pretty tough.
But things were like we had to make special accommodations for
few things that you don't normally have.
There were a lot of fleas in the apartment and we didn't realize, you know, we knew we were getting bit by something.
And my wife, you know, she would always be complaining that there were things in the bed that were crawling on her.

so I never, they weren't bothering me as much, and maybe I had sour blood or something, but she was being bitten by these fleas, and eventually, and of course it was very cold there, and so she had these black tights on that she was sleeping with, and she actually
got one of the fleas trapped in this mesh of these tights that she had on.
And that's when I first really believed that they were fleas there.
So we had to dust the bed down with flea powder.
And eventually, we were able to control that thing.
Yeah, there certainly are some different kinds of challenges that you have.
Did you feel that the locals appreciated your presence?
And what groups did, what groups didn't?
Well, certainly the blind girls appreciated all the attention that they got.
I think the high school students from the Tupac Atari night school genuinely
appreciated all the efforts that we made to try to prepare them for their entrance into college.
Perhaps there was not as much general acceptance of the college students themselves.
By the time you get into college, you get a little more jaded, and I think you can say that
one class was really interesting or you felt that you got some new insights to things because they were taught in a different way than you were used to.
So you can never really judge what kind of impact you're having on the people.
But I think we also provided
a lot of guidance and opportunities for some of the brighter students that were there to try to make it easier for them to find education in other countries or in the United States or

find opportunities for them to pursue their own studies and maybe go on to graduate school and perhaps they wouldn't have thought of those kinds of angles in order to help finance their continued studies.
And I'm sure, of course, those people were all very genuinely appreciative of the Peace Corps efforts.
And of course, all the people that were working in public health and community development and actually making living conditions better for the locals.
That's always something that is appreciated.
But then there were always the feeling that, and particularly in countries like Bolivia, where they had just had a revolution,
They always were very suspicious of Peace Corps volunteers and bringing in outside and foreign ideas because they kind of felt that it was sowing seeds of continuous revolution.
If you teach the Indians a better way of doing things and if you start to generate in them the idea that
nothing is necessarily has to be acceptable or that they can always do better, then it creates a tension which perhaps, you know, does foment some revolutionary type ideas.
And that's always something that was sort of a delicate balance of whether you could
continue the various programs in country or whether they were going to pull the plug because they really didn't trust what was happening.
And a lot of countries decided not to continue Peace Corps, particularly
in countries where there was a ruling class and there was a disadvantaged class of people.

And if you spent too much time trying to improve the conditions of the disadvantaged class and make them feel that they really could do better for themselves, then obviously how far do you go with that before the ruling class is going to say, hey, that's enough of this kind of activity.
This is kind of a broad question, but how did the Peace Corps affect your life positively and negatively, looking back?
Well, it certainly changed my life on many fronts.
First off, I had never really been out of the United States when I joined the Peace Corps program, so it certainly gave me a lot more of outgoing and global perspective than I had before.
And the fact that I
met the woman that I fell in love with and married her in the Peace Corps.
Both of our Peace Corps volunteer experiences were something that we shared a whole lifetime.
I think it has profoundly changed how I view things.
You realize all of the news when you

hear things on the news that are of an international nature, we realize how slanted things can be if you're getting just a news reporting of something, whereas if you're actually in the country and know what's going on, it can be very much different.
So you realize that there's a very difficult time in

actually reporting news and avoiding the slanting of news so that if you're into international affairs you really do have to to look at a lot of different reports of things and make your own judgment as to what conditions are really like because there is a lot of opportunity to
you know, cut things short and perhaps not come up with the real situation.
I think overall I felt that the Peace Corps experience was very positive for me and I actually
decided that I wanted to become a university educator and go back and get my PhD.
After I did my two years in the Peace Corps, I went back to the University of Missouri and got a PhD.
But at the time that I graduated in 1969, it seemed like there was a lot of competition at that time.

I started writing to various universities to send my application and they would say, you know, we appreciate your application, you're applicant number 134 for a teaching job at various universities throughout the country.
I realized that it was not going to be easy to break into the
teaching at the university level in the U.S. and at the same time I was offered a job to go with an oil company, Pan American Petroleum in Denver, Colorado.
So I just had to make the choice and I decided to go into the petroleum business and that's where I've been ever since.
I found that was something that really appealed to me as well.
So I decided to make a career in that.
And how that came from the effect of the Peace Corps had on you?
Well, it certainly made it more interesting that oil companies were working in many around-the-world type of activities.
And later on, after spending seven years in domestic exploration, I joined the international group and actually went overseas again.
And I lived in Argentina for two years, and I lived in Indonesia and Jakarta for five years.
And I was also in Japan for about nine months.
So I did spend a great deal of time.
And I have made a lot of trips into different foreign countries.
And so I think that the Peace Corps experience just kind of made it a lot easier to think about living and working
environments outside the United States and actually interacting with other cultures and it wasn't nearly as foreign an idea.
So I think it kind of broadened my whole horizon and gave me the feeling that

The world is really a lot smaller than it looks and feels and that people living and doing things in different parts of the world are really very interesting and really not that much different from us.
You just have to understand them and take advantage of all the different ideas and concepts that they have.

After finishing your tour of duty, did you feel that you and the other Peace Corps volunteers you were in contact with, did you feel like you fulfilled the duty that you were sent to do and the promises that you, or commitments you made to the people there?
Well, like I said before, it's always very difficult to judge the effectiveness of any particular Peace Corps program.
The fact that they continued the program for many years after we left I think was at least some indication that the country itself felt that it was fulfilling a need.
Most of the volunteers had generally pretty positive outlooks when they came out.
They felt that it was an advantage both to them and they hoped

equally an advantage to the to the country itself they felt that they had made impact on a lot of the people's lives that they made good friends of in country we also made friends with a lot of the faculty that we worked with and these experiences I think were you know it's always important to transfer
academic ideas from the Peace Corps volunteers to the faculty members and you never really know how important that is.
It's sort of cross-pollination and I think that probably is always healthy.
So overall I think most of the people felt that it was a valuable program.
They felt that they
benefited from it and many of them were eager to, you know, either go to a different Peace Corps environment.
Some even, you know, went to other countries or continued to serve after
their Peace Corps effort was finished in one country.
My sister worked for four years in Tanzania in her assignments, and she felt it was a very positive experience as well.
